In his witness statement, Mr Harrison 
wrote that ‘many murderers revisit the scene of the crime’ and if caught
in the act by police surveillance, this can provide ‘extremely 
important’ evidence to the prosecution.

‘In this case, if the suspect had 
decided to re-visit the scene, to dispose of additional evidence, or to 
move a body that had not yet been found and he realised he was being 
followed, he may have cancelled or postponed his trip,’ he said.

‘He would not care whether he was 
being followed by a “legitimate” surveillance team or one employed by a 
newspaper. The evidence would be lost and the prosecution case 
weakened.’

